  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 9b-16.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(2)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "The outbreak of hostility due to the breach of the sabbatic law.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 9b.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Now it was the sabbath on that day",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The form of the expression implies that it was one of the festival sabbaths rather than the weekly sabbath. These days, however, received the same reverence, and were observed with nearly the same rites and restrictions, as the ordinary sabbaths. This statement is the keynote of the great discourse which fellows, and it is made to prepare the way for the subsequent incidents. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "The Jews",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the authorities, either the rabbis or Sanhedrists who were present in the crowd which gathered round the pool of Bethesda, or filled the neighbouring courts, are to be distinguished from \"the multitude,\" or from the people generally. The designation evidently means the leading folk, the social censors, the hierarchy, who very soon displayed in marked fashion their jealousy and hatred of Jesus. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The Jews therefore said to the man who",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "had been healed, It is sabbath,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "it is not lawful for thee to carry thy bed.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Judging by the letter of the Law (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 20:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and Exodus 35:3), and by the precedents of Scripture (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 15:32-35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and by the special injunctions of the prophets (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 17:21-23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 13:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.), the man was infringing a positive command. Rabbinism had indeed declared that, in cases affecting life and health, the law of the sabbath was legitimately held in abeyance; but this relaxation was so hedged about with restrictions that the poor man and the layman were unable to apply the rules. The rabbinic interpretations of the sabbatic law concerning burden bearing were so intricate and sophistical that the entire majesty of the law, and the merciful intent of the prohibition, were concealed and vitiated. Apart from these complications, the man was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "prima facie",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " disobeying the letter of the law. 'Shabbath,' fol. 6, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", declares that if unwittingly a burden was carried on the sabbath, the transgressor was bound to bring a sin offering; if with knowledge, he must be stoned. John 5:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
